# ssh-agent-proxy configuration.
#
# Install this file at ~/.config/ssh-agent-proxy/env with mode 0600:
#
#     install -d -m 0700 ~/.config/ssh-agent-proxy
#     install -m 0600 contrib/systemd/env.example ~/.config/ssh-agent-proxy/env
#     $EDITOR ~/.config/ssh-agent-proxy/env
#
# systemd loads this file via EnvironmentFile= before the service starts.
#
# ssh-agent-proxy forwards sign requests to a local ssh-agent. It holds no
# key material of its own; your private key lives in whatever process is
# serving the agent (typically 1Password Desktop, but any ssh-agent-
# compatible implementation works). This file tells the proxy where to
# find that agent.

# REQUIRED. Path to the ssh-agent Unix socket. On Linux, 1Password
# Desktop exposes this at one of:
#     ~/.1password/agent.sock                      (Linux, $HOME/.1password)
#     $XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/1password/agent.sock        (Linux, some distros)
# On macOS:
#     ~/Library/Group Containers/2BUA8C4S2C.com.1password/t/agent.sock
#
# If you set SSH_AUTH_SOCK in your shell already, leave SSH_AGENT_PROXY_UPSTREAM
# unset and the proxy will honor it. systemd user services do not inherit
# your shell env, so for a service install you probably want to set it
# here explicitly.
SSH_AUTH_SOCK=%h/.1password/agent.sock

# SSH_AGENT_PROXY_UPSTREAM (optional) overrides SSH_AUTH_SOCK if set. Use
# this if you want to force a specific agent path without touching the
# SSH_AUTH_SOCK convention (e.g. to route through a non-1Password agent
# while keeping your terminal sessions on 1Password).
#SSH_AGENT_PROXY_UPSTREAM=%h/.1password/agent.sock

# Optional. Restrict the proxy to signing with one specific key from
# the agent. Without this, the first key the agent advertises is used
# (which is usually fine for a single-identity dev machine). Either
# paste the OpenSSH authorized_keys line directly, or set
# SSH_AGENT_PROXY_PUBKEY_FILE to a path.
#SSH_AGENT_PROXY_PUBKEY=ssh-ed25519 AAAA... user@host
#SSH_AGENT_PROXY_PUBKEY_FILE=%h/.ssh/git_signing_key.pub

# Optional. Listen address for the HTTP server. Loopback-only by
# default. Change to 0.0.0.0:7221 if you need containers on a bridge
# network to reach the proxy via --add-host=host.docker.internal:host-gateway
# (this exposes the proxy to any process on the host — prefer
# --network host when possible).
#SSH_AGENT_PROXY_ADDR=127.0.0.1:7221

# Optional. SSHSIG namespace. Git expects "git"; there's no reason to
# change this unless you're using the proxy for something other than
# git commit signing.
#SSH_AGENT_PROXY_NAMESPACE=git
